{{Left communism sidebar |Concepts}}

'''Revolutionary spontaneity''' (also known as '''spontaneism''') is a tendency to believe that [[social revolution]] can and should occur ''spontaneously'' [[working class|from below]], [[Leaderless resistance|without the aid or guidance]] of a [[vanguard party]], and that it cannot and should not be brought about by the actions of [[cult of personality|individuals]] or [[professional revolutionaries|parties]] who might attempt to foment such a revolution.

In his work ''[[What is to be Done? (pamphlet)|What is to be Done?]]'' (1902), [[Vladimir Lenin]] argued fiercely against revolutionary spontaneity<ref>[http://www.marxists.org/archive/lenin/works/1901/witbd/ii.htm] What Is To Be Done? Ch. 2:The Spontaneity of the Masses and the [[False Consciousness|Consciousness]] of the [[Social Democrats]]</ref> as a dangerous "[[revisionism (Marxism)|revisionist]]" concept that strips away the disciplined nature of [[Marxist philosophy|Marxist political thought]] and leaves it [[arbitrary]] and ineffective. [[Rosa Luxemburg]] and the [[Spartacist League]], which had attempted to overturn [[capitalism]] during the 1919 [[German Revolution]], would become main targets of Lenin's attacks after [[World War I]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.marxists.org/archive/mattick-paul/1949/spontaneity.htm |title=Spontaneity and Organisation |author=Kurasje Council Communism Site |publisher=Marxist.org |accessdate=April 12, 2014}}</ref>

Spontaneism, however, remained a popular theory in opposition to the [[Third International]]'s [[democratic centralism]], and influenced the [[Autonomism|autonomist]] movement in the 1970s. Its influences can be felt in some parts of today's [[alter-globalization]] movement.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}

