{{about||the ships|Massachusetts ship Tyrannicide (1776)|and|French ship Tyrannicide (1793)}}
{{Homicide}}
'''Tyrannicide''' is the killing or [[assassination]] of a [[tyrant]] or unjust ruler, usually for the [[common good]],<ref>Jaucourt, Louis, chevalier de. "Tyrannicide." The Encyclopedia of Diderot & d'Alembert Collaborative Translation Project. Translated by Thomas Zemanek. Ann Arbor: Michigan Publishing, University of Michigan Library, 2009. http://hdl.handle.net/2027/spo.did2222.0001.682. Originally published as "Tyrannicide," Encyclopédie ou Dictionnaire raisonné des sciences, des arts et des métiers, 16:785 (Paris, 1765).</ref> 
and usually by one of the tyrant's subjects.<ref name=ce>{{Cite Catholic Encyclopedia|wstitle=Tyrannicide}}</ref>

The term originally denoted the action of [[Harmodius and Aristogeiton]], who are often called the '''Tyrannicides''', in killing [[Hipparchus (son of Peisistratos)|Hipparchus of Athens]] in 514 BC.<ref name=harmodius>{{cite web |url= http://www.brynmawr.edu/archaeology/guesswho/webb.html |title= The Athenian Tyrannicides: Icons of a Democratic Society |first= E. Kent |last= Webb |work= [[University of Washington]] |date= October 18, 1997 |accessdate= 2008-10-30}}</ref>

==Political theory==
{{See also|Right of revolution}}
Tyrannicide can also be a political theory, and as such dates from antiquity.<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=OIVDAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA25 |title= The recognition policy of the United States |first= Julius Ludwig |last= Goebel |year= 1915 |publisher= [[Columbia University]] |pages= 24–29 |accessdate= October 30, 2008}}</ref> Support for tyrannicide can be found in [[Plutarch]]'s ''Lives'', [[Cicero]]'s ''[[De Officiis]]'',<ref name=Saddam>{{citation|volume=19|publisher=Denv. J. Int'l L. & Pol'y|pages=613|date=1990–1991|title=Assassinating Saddam: A Post-War View from International Law|author=Beres, Louis Rene|url=http://heinonlinebackup.com/hol-cgi-bin/get_pdf.cgi?handle=hein.journals/denilp19&section=31}}</ref> and [[Seneca the Younger|Seneca]]'s ''Hercules Furens''.<ref name=nyt>{{cite news |url= http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/05/11/in-syria-and-beyond-the-tyrant-as-target/ |title= In Syria and Beyond, the Tyrant as Target |first= Feisal G. |last= Mohamed |work= [[The New York Times]] |date= May 11, 2013 |accessdate= May 16, 2013}}</ref> [[Plato]] describes a violent tyrant as the opposite of a good and "true king" in the ''[[Statesman (dialogue)|Statesman]]'',<ref name=nyt/> and while [[Aristotle]] in the ''[[Politics (Aristotle)|Politics]]'' sees it as opposed to all other beneficial forms of government, he also described tyrannicide mainly as an act by those wishing to gain personally from the tyrant's death, while those who act without hope of personal gain or to make a name for themselves are rare.<ref>Aristotle, ''Politics'' X</ref>

Various Christian philosophers and theologians also wrote about tyrannicide. In [[Thomas Aquinas]]'s commentary on the ''[[Sentences]]'' of [[Peter Lombard]], Aquinas gave a defense not only of disobedience to an unjust authority, using as an example Christian martyrs in the Roman Empire, but also of "one who liberates his country by killing a tyrant."<ref>For Aquinas, "when what is ordered by an authority is opposed to the object for which that authority was constituted ... not only is there no obligation to obey the authority, but one is obliged to disobey it, as did the holy martyrs who suffered death rather than obey the impious commands of tyrants." One may even be "praised and rewarded" for being the "one who liberates his country by killing a tyrant." Commentary on the Sentences of Peter Lombard, trans. J.G. Dawson (Oxford, 1959), 44, 2 in O’Donovan, p. 329-30.</ref> The [[Monarchomachs]] in particular developed a theory of tyrannicide, with [[Juan de Mariana]] describing their views in the 1598 work ''De rege et regis institutione,''<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=uOrg3lNOTbkC&pg=PA313 |title= Power and Secret of the Jesuits |first= René |last= Fülöp-Miller |authorlink=René Fülöp-Miller |publisher= Kessinger Publishing |year= 1997 |isbn= 0-7661-0056-1 |accessdate= October 30, 2008 |pages= 313–318}}</ref> in which he wrote, {{nobreak|"[B]oth}} the philosophers and theologians agree, that the prince who seizes the state with force and arms, and with no legal right, no public, civic approval, may be killed by anyone and deprived of his life..."<ref name=Saddam/>

[[File:FirstCommitteeGreatSealReverseLossingDrawing.jpg|thumb|upright|left|[[Benjamin Franklin]]'s suggestion for the [[Great Seal of the United States]] included the phrase "Rebellion to Tyrants is Obedience to God."]]
The [[Jesuit|Jesuistic]] [[casuistry]] developed a similar theory, criticized by [[Blaise Pascal]] in the ''[[Provincial Letters]]''.<ref>Ganns, H. G. [https://archive.org/stream/americancatholic27philuoft#page/334/mode/2up ''"The Jesuits and Tyrannicide,"''] The American Catholic Quarterly Review, Vol. XXVII, 1902.</ref> Before them, the [[Scholasticism|scholastic]] philosopher [[John of Salisbury]] also legitimised tyrannicide, under specific conditions, in the ''[[Policraticus]]'', circa 1159.{{sfn|Voegelin|1989|pp=122–123}} His theory was derived from his idea of the state as a political organism in which all the members cooperate actively in the realization of the common utility and justice. He held that when the ruler of this [[body politic]] behaves tyrannically, failing to perform his characteristic responsibilities, the other limbs and organs are bound by their duty to the public welfare and God to correct and, ultimately, to slay the tyrant.<ref>{{citation|year=1988|volume=50|pages=365–389|publisher=Cambridge University Press|doi=10.1017/S0034670500036305|title=A Duty to Kill: John of Salisbury's Theory of Tyrannicide}}</ref>

In 1408 the theologian [[Jean Petit (theologian)|Jean Petit]] used biblical examples to justify tyrannicide following the murder of [[Louis I, Duke of Orleans]] by Petit's patron [[John the Fearless]], Duke of Burgundy. Petit's thesis was extensively discussed and eventually condemned by the church. ''A Shone Treatise of Politike Power'', written by [[John Ponet]] in 1556, argued that the people are custodians of natural and divine law, and that if governors and kings violated their trust, then they forfeited their power, whether they relinquished their positions voluntarily or whether they had to be removed forcefully.<ref>{{citation|title="Oh, Ye Are For Anarchy!": Consent Theory in the Radical Libertarian Tradition|author=C Watner|publisher=Journal of Libertarian Studies|year=1986|url=https://www.mises.org/journals/jls/8_1/8_1_9.pdf}}</ref> ''[[The Tenure of Kings and Magistrates]]'' by [[John Milton]] in 1649 also described the history of tyrannicide, and a defense of it when appropriate.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dartmouth.edu/~milton/reading_room/tenure/ |title= Milton: The Tenure of Kings and Magistrates |last= Luxon |first= Thomas H., ed. |work= The Milton Reading Room |publisher= [[Dartmouth College]] |date= March 2008 |accessdate= 2008-10-30}}</ref>

[[University of Cambridge|Cambridge's]] David George has also argued that [[terrorism]] is a form of tyranny of which tyrannicide is a negation.<ref>{{citation|title=Distinguishing Classical Tyrannicide from Modern Terrorism|year=1988|volume=50|pages=390–419|publisher=Cambridge University Press|doi=10.1017/S0034670500036317}}</ref> Abraham Lincoln believed that assassinating a leader is morally justified when a people has suffered under a tyrant for an extended period of time and has exhausted all legal and peaceful means of ouster.<ref>{{citation|volume=25|publisher=Cornell Int'l L. J.|pages=401|year=1992|title=Executive Order 12,333: The Permissibility of an American Assassination of a Foreign Leader|author=Johnson, Boyd M. III|url=http://heinonlinebackup.com/hol-cgi-bin/get_pdf.cgi?handle=hein.journals/cintl25&section=19}}</ref>

==History==
{{See also|l1=List of regicides|Regicide#Other regicides}}
{| align=right
|[[File:Tiranicidas 04.JPG|thumb|upright|Statue of Harmodius and Aristogeiton]]
|}
Throughout history, many leaders have died under the pretext of tyrannicide. [[Hipparchus (tyrant)|Hipparchus]], one of the last Greek leaders to use the title of "[[list of ancient Greek tyrants|tyrant]]," was assassinated in 514 BC by [[Harmodius and Aristogeiton]], the original tyrannicides.{{sfn|Law|2009|p=18}}<ref name=harmodius/> Since then "tyrant" has been a pejorative term, lacking objective criteria. Many rulers and heads of state have been considered as such by their enemies but not by their adherents and supporters. For example, when [[John Wilkes Booth]] [[assassination of Abraham Lincoln|assassinated Abraham Lincoln]] in 1865, he wrote how he considered [[Abraham Lincoln|Lincoln]] a tyrant while comparing himself to [[Marcus Junius Brutus]],{{sfn|Booth|2000|p=17}} who stabbed the [[Roman dictator]] [[Julius Caesar]] in 44 BC.{{sfn|Law|2009|p=23}}

Tyrannicides have a poor record of achieving their intended outcome. Caesar's death, for example, failed to bring a return to republican power, and instead led to the [[Roman Empire]], but it galvanized later assassins like Booth. Several of Caesar's successors (as Roman Emperors) were also killed for their tyrannical actions, including [[Caligula]], who was stabbed in 41 by [[Cassius Chaerea]] and other [[Praetorian Guard]]s,<ref name=montefiore/> and [[Domitian]], stabbed in 96 by a steward of [[Flavia Domitilla (saint)|Flavia Domitilla]] named Stephanus.{{sfn|Law|2009|p=26}} Many attempts on [[Commodus]]'s life in the late 2nd century failed, including the one instigated by his own sister [[Lucilla]], but he ultimately fell victim to his own excess by a successful murderous coup.<ref>[[Cassius Dio]], [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Cassius_Dio/71*.html Roman History], 71.1, 3; 73.4.4-5.</ref>  After the [[fall of the Western Roman Empire]], tyrannicide continued in the [[Byzantine Empire]] when Emperor [[Andronikos I Komnenos]], was tied to a pillar, beaten, and dismembered by a mob in 1185.<ref name=montefiore/>

Tyrannicide has also been connected to revolution, with many taking place during successful revolutions, and others sparking revolutionary upheavals. In the midst of the [[French Revolution]], [[Maximilien Robespierre]], took power as the [[List of Presidents of the National Convention|President of the National Convention]], but after leading the [[Reign of Terror]] from 1793 to 1794, he was executed by beheading by the [[National Convention]]. The [[Romanian Revolution of 1989|Romanian Revolution]], one of the [[Revolutions of 1989]], enabled a group of defected soldiers to capture [[Nicolae Ceauşescu]], the country's communist leader, and to stage a trial after which he was executed by a firing squad of paratroopers Ionel Boeru, Georghin Octavian and Dorin-Marian Cirlan.{{sfn|Graubard|1999|pp=72–73}}

Many assassins have been killed in the act, such as [[Rigoberto López Pérez]], who shot [[Nicaragua]]n dictator [[Anastasio Somoza García]] in 1956.{{sfn|Borge|1992|p=54}} Others were prosecuted for the killing: [[Antonio de la Maza]] and his conspirators were executed after their shooting of [[Rafael Trujillo]], dictator of the [[Dominican Republic]] in 1961,{{sfn|Diederich|1990|p=20}} as was [[Kim Jaegyu]], who [[Assassination of Park Chung-hee|shot]] [[South Korea]]n dictator [[Park Chung-hee]] in 1979.<ref>{{cite news |title= Hearts and Minds; Without Kim Jae-kyu? The Morality of Tyrannicide |work= [[Korea Times]] |date= July 18, 2000}}</ref> Five of the members of [[Young Bosnia]] who were involved with the [[Assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria|assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand in Sarajevo]] were sentenced to death by hanging, while eleven were sentenced to various years in prison, including [[Gavrilo Princip]] who fired the fatal shot. [[Khalid Islambouli]] was one of three members of [[Egyptian Islamic Jihad]] executed for the [[assassination of Anwar Sadat]], the autocratic [[President of Egypt]] in 1981.<ref>{{cite journal |title= The Sorrows of Egypt: A Tale of Two Men |journal= [[Foreign Affairs]] |publisher= [[Council on Foreign Relations]] |date=September–October 1995 |first= Fouad |last= Ajami}}</ref> Even both Hipparchus's assassins were themselves killed, Harmodius on the spot and Aristogeiton after being tortured, and the [[Assassination of Julius Caesar|major conspirators]] in the plot to kill Caesar were likewise killed or forced to commit suicide.

Outright revolt was the context for other tyrannicides, and allowed individual killers to escape or remain anonymous. During [[World War II]] and the [[Italian resistance movement]], [[Walter Audisio]] claimed to have led his team of partisans in the abduction and execution by firing squad of [[Benito Mussolini]] in 1945.<ref name=montefiore/><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,804084,00.html |title= What Price Brutus? |work= [[Time Magazine]] |date= April 7, 1947 |accessdate= October 31, 2011}}</ref> The circumstances remain clouded, though Audisio was later elected to both the [[Italian Chamber of Deputies]] and the [[Italian Senate]]. In 1990, [[Samuel Doe]], the [[President of Liberia]] was tortured to his death. In 1996, during their takeover of Afghanistan, [[Taliban]] soldiers captured [[Mohammad Najibullah]], the President of the Soviet-backed [[Democratic Republic of Afghanistan]], and dragged him to death. [[Saddam Hussein]], [[President of Iraq]] [[Execution of Saddam Hussein|was executed]] in 2006. During the [[2011 Libyan civil war]], Libyan leader [[Muammar Gaddafi]], the self-titled "Brother Leader and Guide of the Revolution," was killed in the [[Battle of Sirte (2011)|Battle of Sirte]], in unclear circumstances.<ref name=montefiore>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/27/opinion/qaddafi-and-the-lives-of-tyrants.html |title= Dictators Get the Deaths They Deserve |first= Simon Sebag |last= Montefiore |work= [[The New York Times]] |date= October 26, 2011 |accessdate= October 31, 2011}}</ref>

==Literature==
Tyrannicide is a popular [[Trope (literature)|literary trope]]. Many works of fiction deal with the struggle of an individual or group of individuals to overthrow and kill an unjust tyrant. Often the tyranny is caused by an usurper to a royal throne, where the conclusion restores the proper heir. [[Children's literature]] frequently deals with the subject. [[Folklore|Folk tales]] like [[The Nutcracker]] include the act, as do some video games series, like [[The Legend of Zelda (series)|The Legend of Zelda]] and [[Star Fox (series)|Star Fox]]. Examples in Disney animation include ''[[The Lion King]]'' and ''[[Aladdin (1992 Disney film)|Aladdin]]'' which both involve the tyrannical takeover of a monarchy and its overhaul. Fantasy works like ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]'', ''[[The Chronicles of Narnia]]'', ''[[The Brothers Lionheart]]'', ''[[A Song of Ice and Fire]]'' and science-fiction series like ''[[Star Wars]]'' and ''[[Doctor Who]]'' all deal with the killing of tyrants. Besides ''[[Julius Caesar (play)|Julius Caesar]]'', a number of [[William Shakespeare]]'s plays deal with the subject, including ''[[Hamlet]]'', ''[[Macbeth]]'', and ''[[Richard III]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://rmmla.wsu.edu/ereview/60.2/reviews/rasmussen.asp |title= Tyranny in Shakespeare |first= Mary Ann |last= McGrail |work= Utah Valley State College |year= 2001 |accessdate= 2008-09-18 |deadurl= yes |archiveurl= https://archive.is/20120802123506/http://rmmla.wsu.edu/ereview/60.2/reviews/rasmussen.asp |archivedate= 2012-08-02 |df=  }}</ref>
Also the [[Italy|Italian]] dramatist, poet and philosopher [[Vittorio Alfieri]] has devoted much of his work on this issue.<ref>Gérard Chalian, Arnaud Blin, ''The History of Terrorism: From Antiquity to Al Qaeda'', p.82, 2007.</ref>

